    explanation: "This question tests your knowledge of the sliding filament theory at the molecular level. Here is the sequence of events:\n\nAt rest, a protein called tropomyosin physically blocks the binding sites on actin (the thin filament), preventing myosin heads from attaching. When a nerve signal arrives at the muscle, calcium ions (Ca²⁺) flood into the muscle cell. Ca²⁺ binds to troponin (a regulatory protein attached to tropomyosin). This causes troponin to change its shape, which physically moves tropomyosin aside — uncovering the binding sites on actin. Now myosin heads can attach to actin, form cross-bridges, and pull — generating force and shortening the muscle.\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **B. Acetylcholine (ACh) is released** — ACh is released earlier in the process, from the motor neuron into the neuromuscular junction. It is what triggers the release of Ca²⁺. Ca²⁺ binding to troponin comes after ACh has already done its job.\n- **C. The cross-bridge disengages** — Cross-bridge disengagement (detachment) requires ATP, not Ca²⁺. Ca²⁺ binding causes attachment, not detachment.\n- **D. ATP hydrolyses to ADP** — ATP hydrolysis powers the \"cocking\" (energising) of the myosin head so it is ready to attach. This also happens before Ca²⁺ binding causes attachment; it does not happen as a result of Ca²⁺ binding to troponin.\n\n**Contraction sequence in order:**\n\nNerve impulse → ACh released → Ca²⁺ released from sarcoplasmic reticulum → Ca²⁺ binds troponin → Tropomyosin shifts → Actin binding sites uncovered → Myosin attaches → Cross-bridge cycling (powered by ATP) → Muscle shortens",
