    explanation: "The epiphysis (plural: epiphyses; from Greek epi- = upon + physis = growth) is the rounded end of a long bone. Each long bone has two epiphyses (proximal and distal). The epiphysis is made of cancellous (spongy) bone covered by a thin layer of hyaline cartilage (articular cartilage) where it meets a joint. In growing children, the epiphyseal plate (growth plate) separates the epiphysis from the diaphysis and is where bone length increases.\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **A. The shaft of a long bone** — The shaft (the long cylindrical middle section) is the diaphysis. Di- = through/two; the diaphysis is the elongated central tube between the two epiphyses.\n- **B. The line that separates the shaft from the end** — This is the epiphyseal line (in adults) or epiphyseal plate (in children — the growth plate). It marks the boundary, not the end itself.\n- **C. The membrane that surrounds a bone** — This is the periosteum — a tough fibrous membrane covering the outer surface of bone (except at joints). It contains blood vessels, nerves, and bone-forming cells.\n\n**Key long bone anatomy terms:**\n\nEpiphysis (end) ← Epiphyseal plate/line (boundary) ← Diaphysis (shaft) → Epiphyseal plate/line → Epiphysis (end)\n\nPeriosteum = outer covering | Medullary cavity = hollow inside",
