    sourcePaper: "September 2023 Past Paper - Paper 2",
    explanation: "The electrical signal from the atria must cross the fibrous skeleton of the heart (a non-conducting barrier between atria and ventricles) to reach the ventricles. The only pathway that allows this conduction is the atrioventricular (AV) bundle (also called the Bundle of His). The AV bundle originates at the AV node and travels through the interventricular septum before dividing into left and right bundle branches, which then spread through the Purkinje fibre network.\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **A. Gap junctions** — Gap junctions allow rapid spread of signals within the atria and within the ventricles, but they cannot bridge the fibrous non-conducting barrier between atria and ventricles. The only route across is the AV bundle.\n- **B. Purkinje fibres** — Purkinje fibres are the final distribution network within the ventricles, rapidly spreading the signal through the ventricular walls. They receive the signal after it has already crossed via the AV bundle — they are downstream.\n- **C. Intercalated discs** — These are the junctional structures between adjacent cardiac muscle cells (containing gap junctions and desmosomes). They are important for cell-to-cell conduction but, again, cannot cross the non-conducting fibrous skeleton between atria and ventricles.\n\n**Cardiac conduction pathway:**\n\nSA node → Atria (gap junctions + internodal pathways) → AV node → AV Bundle (Bundle of His) → Left & Right Bundle Branches → Purkinje fibres → Ventricular muscle",
