    explanation: "Positive feedback is a mechanism in which the body's response to a change amplifies or intensifies that same change — driving the variable further away from its starting point until a specific endpoint is reached. It does NOT maintain homeostasis; instead, it drives a process to completion.\n\n**Classic examples:**\n\n- **Childbirth:** Uterine contractions stretch the cervix → oxytocin release increases → more contractions → more oxytocin → until the baby is born\n- **Blood clotting:** Platelets aggregate → release chemicals that attract more platelets → larger and larger plug until bleeding stops\n- **Nerve impulse:** Sodium influx → more Na⁺ channels open → more influx → action potential fires fully\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **A** — \"The process by which the body maintains homeostasis\" describes homeostasis in general — which is primarily maintained through negative feedback. Positive feedback is the exception.\n- **B** — \"The body's response opposes the stimulus\" is the definition of negative feedback — the dominant mechanism for homeostasis.\n- **D** — This describes the general homeostatic control system components (integrating centre, effector, receptor) — not specifically positive feedback.",
