    explanation: "The active form of vitamin D, calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D), is essential for the intestinal absorption of calcium (and phosphate). It does this by stimulating the production of calcium-binding proteins in intestinal cells (enterocytes) that allow calcium ions to cross from the gut into the bloodstream. Without adequate vitamin D, even a calcium-rich diet cannot prevent bone weakening because calcium cannot be absorbed. Deficiency leads to rickets in children and osteomalacia in adults.\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **A. Required for haemostasis** — Blood clotting requires vitamin K (activates clotting factors), not vitamin D.\n- **C. Required for erythropoiesis** — Red blood cell production requires vitamin B12 and folic acid (for DNA synthesis) and iron (for haemoglobin). Vitamin D is not directly involved.\n- **D. Required for uptake of intrinsic factor** — Intrinsic factor is a protein produced by the stomach that is needed for absorption of vitamin B12 in the ileum — not related to vitamin D.",
