    subtopic: "Feedback Mechanisms",
    section: "Introductory Block",
    sourcePaper: "September 2023 Past Paper - Paper 2",
    explanation: "In a homeostatic feedback loop, the afferent pathway carries the signal from the receptor (the sensor that detects a change in the internal environment) toward the integrating centre (e.g., the brain or spinal cord). It is the incoming or sensory information pathway.\n\nAfferent comes from Latin ad- (toward) + ferre (to carry) = \"carrying toward\" (the control centre).\n\n**Homeostatic loop components:**\n\n| Component | Role |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| Receptor (sensor) | Detects the stimulus/change |\n| Afferent pathway | Carries signal TO the integrating centre |\n| Integrating centre | Processes information and determines response |\n| Efferent pathway | Carries response FROM integrating centre to effector |\n| Effector | Produces the corrective response |",
    memoryTip: "AFFERENT = ARRIVES at the control centre (incoming). EFFERENT = EXITS the control centre (outgoing). Think: A for Arrive, E for Exit.",
