    sourcePaper: "September 2023 Past Paper - Paper 2",
    explanation: "Thin myofilaments contain three proteins working together:\n\n1. **Actin** — the structural backbone; a chain of globular proteins twisted into a double helix. Each actin molecule has a myosin-binding site that is normally blocked at rest.\n2. **Tropomyosin** — a thread-like regulatory protein that winds along the actin strand and physically blocks the myosin-binding sites at rest, preventing unwanted contraction.\n3. **Troponin** — a complex of three proteins attached to tropomyosin at regular intervals. When calcium ions (Ca²⁺) bind to troponin, it shifts tropomyosin away, uncovering the binding sites on actin and allowing contraction to begin.\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **A. Actin only** — Incomplete. Tropomyosin and troponin are also essential components of thin filaments — they are the regulatory proteins.\n- **B. Actin and tropomyosin** — Missing troponin, which is the Ca²⁺-sensing trigger of the whole regulatory system.\n- **D. Includes myosin** — Myosin is a THICK filament protein, not thin. Thick filaments = myosin only. Thin filaments = actin + tropomyosin + troponin.",
    memoryTip: "THIN filaments = Actin + Troponin + Tropomyosin (ATT). THICK filaments = Myosin alone (M). 'Thin = A Team of Three. Thick = just Myosin (Mighty).",
