    explanation: "Colloid osmotic pressure (also called oncotic pressure) is the osmotic pressure created specifically by large protein molecules dissolved in plasma — particularly albumin. Because proteins are too large to cross capillary walls, they remain inside the blood vessel and exert an osmotic pull, drawing water back into the capillary from the surrounding tissues. This force is critical for preventing oedema (tissue swelling).\n\n**Why each option is wrong:**\n\n- **A. Due to all dissolved particles** — This describes total osmotic pressure or osmolarity of the blood — the combined effect of all dissolved particles (ions, glucose, urea, proteins). Colloid osmotic pressure specifically refers only to the contribution of proteins (colloids).\n- **B. Difference between arterial and venous end pressures** — This describes the drop in hydrostatic pressure along the length of a capillary, not colloid osmotic pressure.\n- **C. Difference between capillary and interstitial fluid pressures** — This describes hydrostatic pressure across the capillary wall, which drives fluid out of capillaries. Colloid osmotic pressure works in the opposite direction (pulling fluid back in).",
