    explanation: "The afferent pathway carries information from the receptor (which detects a stimulus or change in the internal environment) toward the integrating centre (the brain or spinal cord). It is the signal going in — the incoming or sensory limb of the feedback loop.\n\nAfferent = Latin for \"carrying toward\" (toward the control centre).\n\nThis question is essentially identical to Q38, and the answer is the same. This is intentional — it is a high-yield topic that the examiners emphasise.\n\n**Full homeostatic loop — every component:**\n\n| Step | Component | Role |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| 1 | Stimulus | Creates a change in a variable |\n| 2 | Receptor/sensor | Detects the change |\n| 3 | Afferent pathway | Carries signal TO the integrating centre |\n| 4 | Integrating centre | Processes info, decides on response |\n| 5 | Efferent pathway | Carries response FROM integrating centre TO effector |\n| 6 | Effector | Produces the corrective response |\n| 7 | Response | Restores variable toward set point |",
